    "Orthostatic hypotension affects approximately 20% of adults over age 65 and up to 30-50% of nursing home residents.",
    "In cirrhosis patients, orthostatic hypotension is extremely common (30-60%) due to splanchnic vasodilation, reduced effective circulating volume, and autonomic neuropathy.",
    "The mechanism of OH in cirrhosis involves excessive nitric oxide production, leading to splanchnic arterial vasodilation that 'steals' blood volume from the systemic circulation.",
    "Standing triggers the baroreceptor reflex: blood pools in lower extremities → reduced venous return → decreased cardiac output → baroreceptor activation → sympathetic outflow → vasoconstriction + increased heart rate.",
    "Autonomic failure disrupts this compensatory mechanism — the sympathetic nervous system fails to increase heart rate and vascular resistance adequately upon standing.",
    "Neurogenic orthostatic hypotension (nOH) results from failure of norepinephrine release from sympathetic neurons — HR fails to increase >15 bpm despite BP drop.",
    "Non-neurogenic OH results from volume depletion, medications, or cardiac causes — the heart rate typically increases >15 bpm as a compensatory response.",
    "Distinguishing neurogenic from non-neurogenic OH: if HR rise is <15 bpm with BP drop ≥30 mmHg systolic, neurogenic autonomic failure is likely.",
    "Common medications causing OH include: diuretics, alpha-blockers, antihypertensives, nitrates, antidepressants (TCAs, MAOIs), antipsychotics, opioids, and PDE5 inhibitors.",
    "In cirrhosis, paracentesis can transiently worsen orthostatic hypotension by further reducing effective circulating volume — albumin replacement helps prevent this.",
    "Post-paracentesis orthostatic symptoms (dizziness, lightheadedness on standing) are early signs of PPCD — blood pressure monitoring in supine and standing positions is warranted.",
